[2] Netherlands ex Saudi Arabia - RIVM [National Institute for Public Health and the Environment - Netherlands]
Date: 14 May 2014
Source: RIVM [edited]
http://www.rivm.nl/Documenten_en_publicaties/Algemeen_Actueel/Nieuwsberichten/2014/Eerste_MERS_patient_in_Nederland


On 13 May [2014], the RIVM and the Erasmus MC [identified] the 1st infection with the MERS coronavirus in a Dutch patient. He became infected during a visit to Saudi Arabia and is currently hospitalized in the Medical Center Haaglanden Westeinde. The patient is being cared for in strict isolation. His health condition is stable. All the people who have had contact with the patient are identified and are being [traced]. These people's health condition is being monitored.

MERS infections can cause severe respiratory symptoms, especially in people with other health problems. Diarrhea symptoms may also occur. Human-to-human transmission of the MERS coronavirus is rare, except in close contact with patients and through unprotected care of seriously ill people.

Since 2012, there has been an outbreak of a new MERS coronavirus (Middle East respiratory syndrome) in the Middle East. Meanwhile, more than 500 patients in the Middle East have been reported to the World Health Organization. In April and May 2014, there has been a sharp increase in the number of reports in the Middle East. The vast majority of reports come from this region (especially Saudi Arabia, as well as Qatar, Jordan, Oman, Yemen and United Arab Emirates). Since last year [2013], there have also been some patients diagnosed in the United Kingdom, France, Italy, Greece, Philippines, Malaysia, Kuwait, Tunisia, Egypt, Germany and the United States. These were travelers who were [infected] in the Middle East. It is not unexpected that there is now a patient in the Netherlands. MERS coronavirus is, therefore, a notifiable infectious disease.

--
